Please join us for the next in the Conversation in Food Justice Series, brought to you by The Apsen Institute and Share Our Strength/No Kid Hungry!⁠
⁠
In cities across America, hunger is not distributed equally. A long history of racialized policies and infrastructure guiding city planning and design have limited economic opportunity and food access in communities of color, creating neighborhoods where affordable, healthy food is scarce.⁠
⁠
In this session, we’ll examine how America’s history of unequal housing and urban development have contributed to food insecurity. We’ll also hear from the community leaders⁠
who are redesigning cities and neighborhoods to ensure that all people have access to healthy, affordable food.⁠
⁠
Click the link in my bio to register, and stay on for the post-session chat with me and Elliot Gaskins of Share Our Strength!
